The `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` web component is the modern replacement for the legacy `Autocomplete` widget. The two most common mistakes developers make are using the wrong event name (`gmp-placeselect` instead of the correct `gmp-select`) and trying to read `event.place` directly ŌĆö you actually need to call `placePrediction.toPlace()` from the event payload, then `fetchFields()` to retrieve the data you need [Source 1].

Here's a complete working example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
  <gmp-place-autocomplete id="pac"></gmp-place-autocomplete>
  <div id="result"></div>
  <gmp-map id="map" center="40.7128,-74.0060" zoom="12" map-id="DEMO_MAP_ID"></gmp-map>

  <script>
    async function init() {
      await google.maps.importLibrary("places");
      const { AdvancedMarkerElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("marker");

      const pac = document.getElementById("pac");
      const map = document.getElementById("map");
      let marker;

      pac.addEventListener("gmp-select", async ({ placePrediction }) => {
        // Step 1: convert prediction to a Place object
        const place = placePrediction.toPlace();

        // Step 2: fetch only the fields you need (field mask is required)
        await place.fetchFields({
          fields: ["displayName", "formattedAddress", "location"],
        });

        // Step 3: use the place data
        document.getElementById("result").textContent =
          `${place.displayName} ŌĆö ${place.formattedAddress}`;

        // Step 4: drop a marker
        if (marker) marker.map = null;
        marker = new AdvancedMarkerElement({
          map: map.innerMap,
          position: place.location,
          title: place.displayName,
        });
      });

      // Always handle errors
      pac.addEventListener("gmp-error", (e) => console.error(e));
    }
    init();
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

A few important things to note:

- **Session tokens are handled automatically** ŌĆö the element internally manages `AutocompleteSessionToken`s, grouping keystrokes and the subsequent `fetchFields()` call into a single billed session. You don't need to create or pass tokens yourself [Source 3].
- **Use `AdvancedMarkerElement`**, not the deprecated `google.maps.Marker`, for any markers you place based on autocomplete results [Source 1].
- **Field masks matter for billing** ŌĆö only the fields you list in `fetchFields()` are returned and billed. If you omit a field, you won't get it back silently [Source 4].

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New)](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)

The recommended approach for new React/Next.js projects is to use **`@vis.gl/react-google-maps`** (team-maintained, StrictMode-safe, built around `AdvancedMarkerElement`) or **`@googlemaps/js-api-loader` v2** if you need lower-level control [Source 1]. Avoid the legacy `new Loader({...}).load()` pattern or manually injecting `<script>` tags inside `useEffect` ŌĆö both cause double-injection issues with React StrictMode [Source 2].

Here are both approaches:

---

### Option A: `@vis.gl/react-google-maps` (recommended for new projects)

The simplest path ŌĆö wrap your app in `<APIProvider>` and drop in `<Map>` and `<AdvancedMarker>` components directly [Source 3]:

```tsx
// app/components/StoreMap.tsx
'use client'; // Next.js App Router ŌĆö required

import { APIProvider, Map, AdvancedMarker, Pin } from '@vis.gl/react-google-maps';

const center = { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 };

export default function StoreMap() {
  const apiKey = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY!;

  return (
    <APIProvider apiKey={apiKey} libraries={['marker']}>
      <Map
        defaultCenter={center}
        defaultZoom={12}
        mapId={process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_MAP_ID}
        style={{ width: '100%', height: 480 }}
        gestureHandling="cooperative"
      >
        <AdvancedMarker position={center} title="New York City">
          <Pin background="#EA4335" borderColor="#B31412" glyphColor="#fff" />
        </AdvancedMarker>
      </Map>
    </APIProvider>
  );
}
```

---

### Option B: `@googlemaps/js-api-loader` v2 (lower-level control)

Use `setOptions` + `importLibrary` ŌĆö both are idempotent, so StrictMode double-invocation is safe [Source 3]:

```tsx
// app/components/RawMap.tsx
'use client';

import { useEffect, useRef } from 'react';
import { setOptions, importLibrary } from '@googlemaps/js-api-loader';

// Run once at module scope ŌĆö guard against SSR
if (typeof window !== 'undefined') {
  setOptions({ key: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY!, v: 'weekly' });
}

export default function RawMap() {
  const containerRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
  const mapRef = useRef<google.maps.Map | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false;

    (async () => {
      const [{ Map }, { AdvancedMarkerElement }] = await Promise.all([
        importLibrary('maps') as Promise<google.maps.MapsLibrary>,
        importLibrary('marker') as Promise<google.maps.MarkerLibrary>,
      ]);
      if (cancelled || !containerRef.current) return;

      const map = new Map(containerRef.current, {
        center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
        zoom: 12,
        mapId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_MAP_ID,
      });
      mapRef.current = map;

      new AdvancedMarkerElement({ map, position: map.getCenter()!, title: 'NYC' });
    })();

    // Cleanup: cancel async work, release map reference
    return () => {
      cancelled = true;
      mapRef.current = null;
    };
  }, []);

  return <div ref={containerRef} style={{ width: '100%', height: 480 }} />;
}
```

---

